{"questionId":"2722726","questionHtml":"<p>Find the range of values for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> such that there are two possible positions for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempts to solve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">a</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">a</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for their ‘<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo></math>’ or their ‘<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo></math>’. For example, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> or equivalent.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>≤</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>≤</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>≤</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>≤</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>≠</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> corresponds to only one possible position for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2722726","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ2.9c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the range of values for θ such that there are two possible positions for M.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Unit circle definitions of sin, cos, tan. Exact trig ratios, ambiguous case of sine rule","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.8—Solving trig equations","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.12—Vector definitions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.13—Scalar (dot) product","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.10—Solving equations graphically and analytically"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}